TextBlock.TextLine: Antwerp 29 aug 1682
lond m. Henry Maynard
6 my last the you was on the 26 courant sence red yd off 14 ditto with
invoyce for one bale off cottons p bayes for my share in which you have
creditt: I hope the goods aft stale are shipped aboard smith & that
have diparted by this time. because you shoud net thick meenet tot
incline rather to do all with you onely then with sivirall have resolved
to send the inclosed peist fer 2 bales off cloth kersies from the north
in which pray lett net in fremon or n'hillbe imployed, butt seert
a nece freind, as you iudge woald imorridge a large commission, for
I want in lesthen bo bales a yeare franthe noith, pindar is ni
loading & if these 2 bales coud come with han ift shoud bebest to
dispasch the dosens fiest. for the rest of the goods disired from London
referre you to my fremans & shall exspert all in corformitie I do
muth long fork lack & puch haveing muth need for the goods
onther board: ys bill I have accept & past to yd acctt I shall
remitt. if possible, whilst I desire yd forbeavence as long as you
can off drawing on mee, for I would tame gest out off that way
though, I am att present pressy well charged. yett hopeto overcome
ist & remitt as fommerby as for the boch keeper off which you speake,
Swas aggneed with hun upon condition, that is moessins, the heirees
oft de mons shoud not continess the trade for hewas engaged to their
pleafare, & non om Jacob de mont brotker tho his deseasest masser
reneoos the trade so he is still for boath han & the maison mostuaire
& sence the resolse to rencu, could not hinder his stay there othoo wise
is hould have had han, whoever besire, I do all endea vous & af much
as iff I had him, for I am imployed fran morming till ight
& desire no more, primipally when my endeavour may le answered
nith areasonable ame to my freinds content for thiers is mine en
mal occasions I am desired for a past off the inclosed will sence
a pat presty sary off a sna cloth off a boutt, 8 7â€ž6 tis akinde
oft adall gray ist toke hadde

Antwerpen desen 31 aug 1681
monsr: in antwoort aen den uwen van 21 deser sende aen ul heden per post een
packestien aen ul geaddresseert gemerckt EÂ½ N6 inhoudende ontrens
Æ’ 600 weerde canten om de selve te expedieren per eerste oockasie van schepen
naer doublin aen meester elnatan lomm per naeste post volght noch een

brussel m. G Joseph Sabberton
Antwerp: 21 auy 1682
& in answer to yd off yasterday, I am a shamed for yd compliments,
because finde no reason whuch obliged yon in the least: m. mullar
is not yett come from hollant, his wife hath been with yd procurear
& beeng with a 6i99 belly prevailed on han, to stay out his returne
which the sayes will be nithin 2 a 3 dayes, & sure hee must pay, orbreake
soo wee foum good, to delay fint her execusion till his tertume you
are charged for the f 1200: rec for my 2 bills 8 I have geven you
creditt for the some valeu receaved for you yd which is the nee defull
aft present from I'expecto see you a fa tinday, or maidday nece
endenard Jan franchois bis
Adij primo septene brys 1682
mons. ick hebbe 21 passato, aen ul geschreven sedert geene van ul alleenelij
heden van monst odonnart baert verstaen als dat ul den wisselbreff aen hem
niet en heeft voldaen waer over mij grootelijx verwondere, hij wilt die
weerde wederom hebben soo heb ick hem gebeden te wachten uwe antwoort
als wanneer hem beloofden met de selve soude verstaen dat ul den brief
betaelt hadde, t gene hope sult hebben gedaen, want anders soude ick
daer door groote preiudicie lijden, oversulckx bid ick ul hier in geen
langer uytstel te maken, daer en tusschen soo ben ick te voeden aen
ul op een nieu te crediteren al was het noch soo veel, ende als ul gelieft
over te comen ende een versse partije te coopen dan sullen wij wissel
brieven maken van ontrent de Â£50Â½ ider, ende dat op differenten tijdt
om ul daer mede te beter te accommoderen, ul verscherende van mijn
genegentheyt in ul alsoos wel, ende goeden coop te dienen maer dan
moet ul voor de betaelinge, promte sorge draegen wachtende ul
antwoort blijve
Antwerp: primo epo 1682
hill Ritchard Southell
mons. answer to 90 oft 27 past Iam forry to many resting cloathes, which
indeed & du not enpect, there by ys exente off paying amy thing for
my autt: sure I should thinck thort yd yd pay mente are not so badd
as ours, & that last yearres acctt naght be cleared by this time, fer
I shall not beablese te forbare uisthin a â…“ to draw on you Â£100-
ett least, att 2 uso which I hope you well accept havemg this month
abont Â£1500 of the pay, so expect yo aprobation as for the mill, for
is nott upon mj acctt, he intended to come neitter will I engage for are
penrrie for han, orfor his machines yett am I not a litle engayed
for yd care & the dondems promise & shall wthe lile occasion regaist
mij obligation, inclosed a letter tot my trother, which I opened &
for mid the contents, those monkes might have an intention like the
